[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] In statistical mechanics and mathematics, a **Boltzmann distribution** (also called **Gibbs distribution**) is a probability distribution or probability measure that gives the probability that a system will be in a certain state as a function of that state's energy and the temperature of the system.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The symbol $\propto$ denotes proportionality (see § The distribution for the proportionality constant).
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The term *system* here has a wide meaning; it can range from a collection of "sufficient number" of atoms or a single atom to a macroscopic system such as a natural-gas storage tank.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] Therefore, the Boltzmann distribution can be used to solve a wide variety of problems.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The distribution shows that states with lower energy will always have a higher probability of being occupied.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution is named after Ludwig Boltzmann, who first formulated it in 1868 during his studies of the statistical mechanics of gases in thermal equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution should not be confused with the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution or Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution gives the probability that a system will be in a certain *state* as a function of that state's energy, while the Maxwell–Boltzmann distributions give the probabilities of particle *speeds* or *energies* in ideal gases.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The distribution of energies in a *one-dimensional* gas, however, does follow the Boltzmann distribution.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution is a probability distribution that gives the probability of a certain state as a function of that state's energy and temperature of the system to which the distribution is applied.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] It results from the constraint that the probabilities of all accessible states must add up to 1.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] (These special cases occur when the mean value is either the minimum or maximum of the energies εi.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The partition function can be calculated if we know the energies of the states accessible to the system of interest.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] For atoms the partition function values can be found in the NIST Atomic Spectra Database.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The distribution shows that states with lower energy will always have a higher probability of being occupied than the states with higher energy.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] It also gives the quantitative relationship between the probabilities of the two states being occupied.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The corresponding ratio of populations of energy levels must also take their degeneracies into account.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution is often used to describe the distribution of particles, such as atoms or molecules, over bound states accessible to them.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] For a system consisting of many particles, the probability of a particle being in state i is practically the probability that picking a random particle from that system will find it in state i.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution gives these probability for a system in thermal equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] This equation is of great importance to spectroscopy.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] Spectroscopy observes spectral lines of atoms or molecules undergoing transitions from one state to another.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] In order for this to be possible, there must be some particles in the first state to undergo the transition.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] Their fraction can be estimated from the Boltzmann distribution.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] If it is negligible, the transition is very likely not observed at the temperature for which the calculation was done.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] In general, a larger fraction of molecules in the first state means a higher number of transitions to the second state.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] However, there are other factors that influence the intensity of a spectral line, such as whether it is caused by an allowed or a forbidden transition.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution is a special case of the generalized Boltzmann distribution.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The generalized Boltzmann distribution is used in statistical mechanics to describe canonical ensemble, grand canonical ensemble and isothermal–isobaric ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The generalized Boltzmann distribution is usually derived from the principle of maximum entropy, but there are other derivations.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution appears in statistical mechanics when considering closed systems of fixed composition that are in thermal equilibrium (equilibrium with respect to energy exchange).
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The most general case is the probability distribution for the canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The canonical ensemble has a state probability distribution with the Boltzmann form.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] of a given subsystem state, among the collection.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The canonical ensemble has the property of separability when applied to such a collection: as long as the non-interacting subsystems have fixed composition, then each subsystem's state is independent of the others and is also characterized by a canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] statistical frequency distribution of subsystem states has the Boltzmann form.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] In particle systems, many particles share the same space and regularly change places with each other; the single-particle state space they occupy is a shared space.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] gas of non-interacting particles at equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] This expected number distribution has the Boltzmann form.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution can be introduced to allocate permits in emissions trading.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] A new allocation method, known as the Boltzmann Fair Division, uses the Boltzmann distribution to describe the most probable, natural, and unbiased distribution of emission permits among multiple countries.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] This framework has been further extended to address general problems of distributive justice, including cake-cutting and resource allocation, by allowing flexibility in how factors such as contribution, need, or preference are weighted.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann fair division is recognized for providing a simple yet powerful probabilistic model that can be adapted to various social, political, and economic contexts.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] The Boltzmann distribution has the same form as the multinomial logit model.
[src:statistical-physics/boltzmann-distribution] As a discrete choice model, this is very well known in economics since Daniel McFadden made the connection to random utility maximization.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] In quantum statistics, **Bose–Einstein statistics** (**B–E statistics**) describes one of two possible ways in which a collection of non-interacting identical particles may occupy a set of available discrete energy states at thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The aggregation of particles in the same state, which is a characteristic of particles obeying Bose–Einstein statistics, accounts for the cohesive streaming of laser light and the frictionless creeping of superfluid helium.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The theory of this behaviour was developed (1924–25) by Satyendra Nath Bose, who recognized that a collection of identical and indistinguishable particles could be distributed in this way.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The idea was later adopted and extended by Albert Einstein in collaboration with Bose.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Bose–Einstein statistics apply only to particles that do not follow the Pauli exclusion principle restrictions.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Particles that follow Bose-Einstein statistics are called bosons, which have integer values of spin.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] In contrast, particles that follow Fermi-Dirac statistics are called fermions and have half-integer spins.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] At low temperatures, bosons behave differently from fermions (which obey the Fermi–Dirac statistics) in a way that an unlimited number of them can "condense" into the same energy state.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] This apparently unusual property also gives rise to the special state of matter – the Bose–Einstein condensate.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Fermi–Dirac and Bose–Einstein statistics apply when quantum effects are important and the particles are "indistinguishable".
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Fermi–Dirac statistics applies to fermions (particles that obey the Pauli exclusion principle), and Bose–Einstein statistics applies to bosons.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] As the quantum concentration depends on temperature, most systems at high temperatures obey the classical (Maxwell–Boltzmann) limit, unless they also have a very high density, as for a white dwarf.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Both Fermi–Dirac and Bose–Einstein become Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics at high temperature or at low concentration.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Bose–Einstein statistics was introduced for photons in 1924 by Bose and generalized to atoms by Einstein in 1924–25.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] with *εi* > *μ* and where *ni* is the occupation number (the number of particles) in state *i*, $g_{i}$ is the degeneracy of energy level i, *εi* is the energy of the ith state, *μ* is the chemical potential (zero for a photon gas), *k*B is the Boltzmann constant, and T is the absolute temperature.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] In 1900, Max Planck derived the Planck law to explain blackbody radiation.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] For this purpose, he introduced the concept of quanta of energy.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Władysław Natanson in 1911 concluded that Planck's law requires indistinguishability of "units of energy", although he did not frame this in terms of Einstein's light quanta.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] During this lecture, Bose committed an error in applying the theory, which unexpectedly gave a prediction that agreed with the experiment.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] However, the results it predicted agreed with experiment, and Bose realized it might not be a mistake after all.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] For the first time, he took the position that the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution would not be true for all microscopic particles at all scales.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Thus, he studied the probability of finding particles in various states in phase space, where each state is a little patch having phase volume of *h*3, and the position and momentum of the particles are not kept particularly separate but are considered as one variable.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Bose adapted this lecture into a short article called "Planck's law and the hypothesis of light quanta" and submitted it to the *Philosophical Magazine*.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] However, the referee's report was negative, and the paper was rejected.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Undaunted, he sent the manuscript to Albert Einstein requesting publication in the *Zeitschrift für Physik*.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Einstein immediately agreed, personally translated the article from English into German (Bose had earlier translated Einstein's article on the general theory of relativity from German to English), and saw to it that it was published.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Bose's theory achieved respect when Einstein sent his own paper in support of Bose's to *Zeitschrift für Physik*, asking that they be published together.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The reason Bose produced accurate results was that since photons are indistinguishable from each other, one cannot treat any two photons having equal quantum numbers (e.g., polarization and momentum vector) as being two distinct identifiable photons.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Bose originally had a factor of 2 for the possible spin states, but Einstein changed it to polarization.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] By analogy, if in an alternate universe coins were to behave like photons and other bosons, the probability of producing two heads would indeed be one-third, and so is the probability of getting a head and a tail which equals one-half for the conventional (classical, distinguishable) coins.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Bose's "error" leads to what is now called Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Bose and Einstein extended the idea to atoms and this led to the prediction of the existence of phenomena which became known as Bose–Einstein condensate, a dense collection of bosons (which are particles with integer spin, named after Bose), which was demonstrated to exist by experiment in 1995.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] In the microcanonical ensemble, one considers a system with fixed energy, volume, and number of particles.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] We take a system composed of ${\textstyle N=\sum _{i}n_{i}}$ identical bosons, $n_{i}$ of which have energy $\varepsilon _{i}$ and are distributed over $g_{i}$ levels or states with the same energy $\varepsilon _{i}$ , i.e. $g_{i}$ is the degeneracy associated with energy $\varepsilon _{i}$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The total energy of the system is ${\textstyle E=\sum _{i}n_{i}\varepsilon _{i}}$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Calculation of the number of arrangements of $n_{i}$ particles distributed among $g_{i}$ states is a problem of combinatorics.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] (second law of thermodynamics for a system at equilibrium).
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] which is the form of the Bose-Einstein distribution.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Note that this form holds even for a system of interacting bosons.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The Bose–Einstein distribution, which applies only to a quantum system of non-interacting bosons, is naturally derived from the grand canonical ensemble without any approximations.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] In this ensemble, the system is able to exchange energy and exchange particles with a reservoir (temperature *T* and chemical potential *μ* fixed by the reservoir).
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Due to the non-interacting quality, each available single-particle level (with energy level *ϵ*) forms a separate thermodynamic system in contact with the reservoir.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] That is, the number of particles within the overall system *that occupy a given single particle state* form a sub-ensemble that is also grand canonical ensemble; hence, it may be analysed through the construction of a grand partition function.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Every single-particle state is of a fixed energy, $\varepsilon$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] This formula applies to fermionic systems as well as bosonic systems.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Fermi–Dirac statistics arises when considering the effect of the Pauli exclusion principle: whilst the number of fermions occupying the same single-particle state can only be either 1 or 0, the number of bosons occupying a single particle state may be any integer.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Note that the geometric series is convergent only if $e^{(\mu -\varepsilon )/k_{\text{B}}T}<1$ , including the case where $\varepsilon =0$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] This implies that the chemical potential for the Bose gas must be negative, i.e., $\mu <0$ , whereas the Fermi gas is allowed to take both positive and negative values for the chemical potential.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] As a result, for highly occupied states the standard deviation of the particle number of an energy level is very large, slightly larger than the particle number itself: $\sigma _{N}\approx \langle N\rangle$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] This large uncertainty is due to the fact that the probability distribution for the number of bosons in a given energy level is a geometric distribution; somewhat counterintuitively, the most probable value for *N* is always 0.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] It is also possible to derive approximate Bose–Einstein statistics in the canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] These derivations are lengthy and only yield the above results in the asymptotic limit of a large number of particles.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The reason is that the total number of bosons is fixed in the canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The Bose–Einstein distribution in this case can be derived as in most texts by maximization, but the mathematically best derivation is by the Darwin–Fowler method of mean values as emphasized by Dingle.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The fluctuations of the ground state in the condensed region are however markedly different in the canonical and grand-canonical ensembles.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Suppose we have a number of energy levels, labeled by index i , each level having energy $\varepsilon _{i}$ and containing a total of $n_{i}$ particles.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Suppose each level contains $g_{i}$ distinct sublevels, all of which have the same energy, and which are distinguishable.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] For example, two particles may have different momenta, in which case they are distinguishable from each other, yet they can still have the same energy.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The value of $g_{i}$ associated with level i is called the "degeneracy" of that energy level.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Any number of bosons can occupy the same sublevel.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Let $w(n,g)$ be the number of ways of distributing n particles among the g sublevels of an energy level.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] There is only one way of distributing n particles with one sublevel, therefore $w(n,1)=1$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] For example, the population numbers for two particles in three sublevels are 200, 110, 101, 020, 011, or 002 for a total of six which equals 4!/(2!2!).
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Following the same procedure used in deriving the Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics, we wish to find the set of $n_{i}$ for which *W* is maximised, subject to the constraint that there be a fixed total number of particles, and a fixed total energy.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The maxima of W and $\ln(W)$ occur at the same value of $n_{i}$ and, since it is easier to accomplish mathematically, we will maximise the latter function instead.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Note that the above formula is sometimes written: $n_{i}={\frac {g_{i}}{e^{\varepsilon _{i}/k_{\text{B}}T}/z-1}},$ where $z=\exp(\mu /k_{\text{B}}T)$ is the absolute activity, as noted by McQuarrie.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Also note that when the particle numbers are not conserved, removing the conservation of particle numbers constraint is equivalent to setting $\alpha$ and therefore the chemical potential $\mu$ to zero.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] This will be the case for photons and massive particles in mutual equilibrium and the resulting distribution will be the Planck distribution.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The purpose of these notes is to clarify some aspects of the derivation of the Bose–Einstein distribution for beginners.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The enumeration of cases (or ways) in the Bose–Einstein distribution can be recast as follows.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Consider a game of dice throwing in which there are n dice, with each die taking values in the set $\{1,\dots ,g\}$ , for $g\geq 1$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The constraints of the game are that the value of a die i , denoted by $m_{i}$ , has to be ***greater than or equal to*** the value of die $(i-1)$ , denoted by $m_{i-1}$ , in the previous throw, i.e., $m_{i}\geq m_{i-1}$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Thus a valid sequence of die throws can be described by an *n*-tuple $(m_{1},m_{2},\dots ,m_{n})$ , such that $m_{i}\geq m_{i-1}$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Then the quantity $w(n,g)$ (defined above as the number of ways to distribute n particles among the g sublevels of an energy level) is the cardinality of $S(n,g)$ , i.e., the number of elements (or valid *n*-tuples) in $S(n,g)$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Thus the problem of finding an expression for $w(n,g)$ becomes the problem of counting the elements in $S(n,g)$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Subset $(a)$ is obtained by fixing all indices $m_{i}$ to 1 , except for the last index, $m_{n}$ , which is incremented from 1 to $g=3$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] Due to the constraint $m_{i}\geq m_{i-1}$ on the indices in $S(n,g)$ , the index $m_{4}$ must automatically take values in $\left\{2,3\right\}$ .
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] The construction of subsets $(c)$ and $(d)$ follows in the same manner.
[src:statistical-physics/bose-einstein-statistics] In other words, there is a one-to-one correspondence between the subset $(\beta )$ of $S(4,3)$ and the set $S(3,2)$ .
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In statistical mechanics, a **canonical ensemble** is the statistical ensemble that represents the possible states of a mechanical system in thermal equilibrium with a heat bath at a fixed temperature.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The system can exchange energy with the heat bath, so that the states of the system will differ in total energy.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The principal thermodynamic variable of the canonical ensemble, determining the probability distribution of states, is the absolute temperature (symbol: *T*).
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The ensemble typically also depends on mechanical variables such as the number of particles in the system (symbol: *N*) and the system's volume (symbol: *V*), each of which influence the nature of the system's internal states.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] An ensemble with these three parameters, which are assumed constant for the ensemble to be considered canonical, is sometimes called the ***NVT* ensemble**.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] where *E* is the total energy of the microstate, and *k* is the Boltzmann constant.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The number *F* is the free energy (specifically, the Helmholtz free energy) and is assumed to be a constant for a specific ensemble to be considered canonical.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] However, the probabilities and *F* will vary if different *N*, *V*, *T* are selected.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The free energy *F* serves two roles: first, it provides a normalization factor for the probability distribution (the probabilities, over the complete set of microstates, must add up to one); second, many important ensemble averages can be directly calculated from the function *F*(*N*, *V*, *T*).
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The equations below (in terms of free energy) may be restated in terms of the canonical partition function by simple mathematical manipulations.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] Historically, the canonical ensemble was first described by Boltzmann (who called it a *holode*) in 1884 in a relatively unknown paper.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] It was later reformulated and extensively investigated by Gibbs in 1902.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The canonical ensemble is the ensemble that describes the possible states of a system that is in thermal equilibrium with a heat bath (the derivation of this fact can be found in Gibbs).
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The canonical ensemble applies to systems of any size; while it is necessary to assume that the heat bath is very large (i.e., take a macroscopic limit), the system itself may be small or large.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The condition that the system is mechanically isolated is necessary in order to ensure it does not exchange energy with any external object besides the heat bath.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In general, it is desirable to apply the canonical ensemble to systems that are in direct contact with the heat bath, since it is that contact that ensures the equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] When the total energy is fixed but the internal state of the system is otherwise unknown, the appropriate description is not the canonical ensemble but the microcanonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] For systems where the particle number is variable (due to contact with a particle reservoir), the correct description is the grand canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In statistical physics textbooks for interacting particle systems the three ensembles are assumed to be thermodynamically equivalent: the fluctuations of macroscopic quantities around their average value become small and, as the number of particles tends to infinity, they tend to vanish.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In the latter limit, called the thermodynamic limit, the average constraints effectively become hard constraints.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The assumption of ensemble equivalence dates back to Gibbs and has been verified for some models of physical systems with short-range interactions and subject to a small number of macroscopic constraints.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] Despite the fact that many textbooks still convey the message that ensemble equivalence holds for all physical systems, over the last decades various examples of physical systems have been found for which breaking of ensemble equivalence occurs.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] Moreover, if the system is made up of multiple *similar* parts, then each part has exactly the same distribution as the other parts.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In this way, the canonical ensemble provides exactly the Boltzmann distribution (also known as Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics) for systems of *any number* of particles.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In comparison, the justification of the Boltzmann distribution from the microcanonical ensemble only applies for systems with a large number of parts (that is, in the thermodynamic limit).
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In a system composed of pieces that interact with each other, it is usually not possible to find a way to separate the system into independent subsystems as done in the Boltzmann distribution.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In these systems it is necessary to resort to using the full expression of the canonical ensemble in order to describe the thermodynamics of the system when it is thermostatted to a heat bath.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The canonical ensemble is generally the most straightforward framework for studies of statistical mechanics and even allows one to obtain exact solutions in some interacting model systems.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] A classic example of this is the Ising model, which is a widely discussed toy model for the phenomena of ferromagnetism and of self-assembled monolayer formation, and is one of the simplest models that shows a phase transition.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] Lars Onsager famously calculated exactly the free energy of an infinite-sized square-lattice Ising model at zero magnetic field, in the canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The precise mathematical expression for a statistical ensemble depends on the kind of mechanics under consideration—quantum or classical—since the notion of a "microstate" is considerably different in these two cases.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In quantum mechanics, the canonical ensemble affords a simple description since diagonalization provides a discrete set of microstates with specific energies.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The classical mechanical case is more complex as it involves instead an integral over canonical phase space, and the size of microstates in phase space can be chosen somewhat arbitrarily.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] Example of canonical ensemble for a quantum system consisting of one particle in a potential well.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] Plot of all possible states of this system.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] A canonical ensemble for this system, for the temperature shown.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The states are weighted exponentially in energy.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] Each panel shows an energy-position plot with the various stationary states, along with a side plot showing the distribution of states in energy.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] A statistical ensemble in quantum mechanics is represented by a density matrix, denoted by ${\hat {\rho }}$ .
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] where *Ĥ* is the system's total energy operator (Hamiltonian), and exp() is the matrix exponential operator.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The canonical ensemble can alternatively be written in a simple form using bra–ket notation, if the system's energy eigenstates and energy eigenvalues are known.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] where the *E**i* are the energy eigenvalues determined by *Ĥ*|*ψ**i*⟩ = *E**i*|*ψ**i*⟩.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In other words, a set of microstates in quantum mechanics is given by a complete set of stationary states.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The density matrix is diagonal in this basis, with the diagonal entries each directly giving a probability.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] Example of canonical ensemble for a classical system consisting of one particle in a potential well.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] (upper graph) and energy-position space (lower graph).
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The side plot shows the distribution of states in energy.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In a system of particles, the number of degrees of freedom *n* depends on the number of particles *N* in a way that depends on the physical situation.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] For a three-dimensional monoatomic gas (not molecules), *n* = 3*N*.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In diatomic gases there will also be rotational and vibrational degrees of freedom.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] This integral is taken over the entire phase space.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] In other words, a microstate in classical mechanics is a phase space region, and this region has volume *hnC*.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] This means that each microstate spans a range of energy, however this range can be made arbitrarily narrow by choosing *h* to be very small.
[src:statistical-physics/canonical-ensemble] The phase space integral can be converted into a summation over microstates, once phase space has been finely divided to a sufficient degree.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Fermi–Dirac statistics applies to identical and indistinguishable particles with half-integer spin (1/2, 3/2, etc.), called fermions, in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] For the case of negligible interaction between particles, the system can be described in terms of single-particle energy states.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] A result is the Fermi–Dirac distribution of particles over these states where no two particles can occupy the same state, which has a considerable effect on the properties of the system.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Fermi–Dirac statistics is most commonly applied to electrons, a type of fermion with spin 1/2.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] A counterpart to Fermi–Dirac statistics is Bose–Einstein statistics, which applies to identical and indistinguishable particles with integer spin (0, 1, 2, etc.) called bosons.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] In classical physics, Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics is used to describe particles that are identical and treated as distinguishable.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] For both Bose–Einstein and Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics, more than one particle can occupy the same state, unlike Fermi–Dirac statistics.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Before the introduction of Fermi–Dirac statistics in 1926, understanding some aspects of electron behavior was difficult due to seemingly contradictory phenomena.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] For example, the electronic heat capacity of a metal at room temperature seemed to come from 100 times fewer electrons than were in the electric current.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] It was also difficult to understand why the emission currents generated by applying high electric fields to metals at room temperature were almost independent of temperature.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] The difficulty encountered by the Drude model, the electronic theory of metals at that time, was due to considering that electrons were (according to classical statistics theory) all equivalent.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] In other words, it was believed that each electron contributed to the specific heat an amount on the order of the Boltzmann constant *k*B.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] This problem remained unsolved until the development of Fermi–Dirac statistics.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Fermi–Dirac statistics was first published in 1926 by Enrico Fermi and Paul Dirac.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] According to Max Born, Pascual Jordan developed in 1925 the same statistics, which he called *Pauli statistics*, but it was not published in a timely manner.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] According to Dirac, it was first studied by Fermi, and Dirac called it "Fermi statistics" and the corresponding particles "fermions".
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Fermi–Dirac statistics was applied in 1926 by Ralph Fowler to describe the collapse of a star to a white dwarf.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] In 1927 Arnold Sommerfeld applied it to electrons in metals and developed the free electron model, and in 1928 Fowler and Lothar Nordheim applied it to field electron emission from metals.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Fermi–Dirac statistics continue to be an important part of physics.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] where *k*B is the Boltzmann constant, T is the absolute temperature, *εi* is the energy of the single-particle state i, and μ is the total chemical potential.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] that can be used to express $\mu =\mu (T,N)$ in that $\mu$ can assume either a positive or negative value.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] At zero absolute temperature, μ is equal to the Fermi energy plus the potential energy per fermion, provided it is in a neighbourhood of positive spectral density.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] In the case of a spectral gap, such as for electrons in a semiconductor, the point of symmetry μ is typically called the Fermi level or—for electrons—the electrochemical potential, and will be located in the middle of the gap.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] The Fermi–Dirac distribution is only valid if the number of fermions in the system is large enough so that adding one more fermion to the system has negligible effect on μ.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Since the Fermi–Dirac distribution was derived using the Pauli exclusion principle, which allows at most one fermion to occupy each possible state, a result is that $0<{\bar {n}}_{i}<1$ .
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] From the Fermi–Dirac distribution of particles over states, one can find the distribution of particles over energy.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] When $g_{i}\geq 2$ , it is possible that ${\bar {n}}(\varepsilon _{i})>1$ , since there is more than one state that can be occupied by fermions with the same energy $\varepsilon _{i}$ .
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] The classical regime, where Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics can be used as an approximation to Fermi–Dirac statistics, is found by considering the situation that is far from the limit imposed by the Heisenberg uncertainty principle for a particle's position and momentum.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] For example, in physics of semiconductor, when the density of states of conduction band is much higher than the doping concentration, the energy gap between conduction band and fermi level could be calculated using Maxwell-Boltzmann statistics.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Otherwise, if the doping concentration is not negligible compared to density of states of conduction band, the Fermi–Dirac distribution should be used instead for accurate calculation.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] where h is the Planck constant, and m is the mass of a particle.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] For the case of conduction electrons in a typical metal at T = 300 K (i.e. approximately room temperature), the system is far from the classical regime because ${\bar {R}}\approx {\bar {\lambda }}/25$ .
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] This is due to the small mass of the electron and the high concentration (i.e. small ${\bar {R}}$ ) of conduction electrons in the metal.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Thus Fermi–Dirac statistics is needed for conduction electrons in a typical metal.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Another example of a system that is not in the classical regime is the system that consists of the electrons of a star that has collapsed to a white dwarf.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Although the temperature of white dwarf is high (typically T = 10000 K on its surface), its high electron concentration and the small mass of each electron precludes using a classical approximation, and again Fermi–Dirac statistics is required.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] The Fermi–Dirac distribution, which applies only to a quantum system of non-interacting fermions, is easily derived from the grand canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] In other words, each single-particle level is a separate, tiny grand canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] By the Pauli exclusion principle, there are only two possible microstates for the single-particle level: no particle (energy *E* = 0), or one particle (energy *E* = *ε*).
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] This quantity is important in transport phenomena such as the Mott relations for electrical conductivity and thermoelectric coefficient for an electron gas, where the ability of an energy level to contribute to transport phenomena is proportional to ${\big \langle }(\Delta N)^{2}{\big \rangle }$ .
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] It is also possible to derive Fermi–Dirac statistics in the canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Consider a many-particle system composed of *N* identical fermions that have negligible mutual interaction and are in thermal equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] where $n_{r}$ is called the occupancy number and is the number of particles in the single-particle state r with energy $\varepsilon _{r}$ .
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] The summation is over all possible single-particle states r .
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] where $\beta =1/k_{\text{B}}T$ , $e^{-\beta E_{R}}$ is called the Boltzmann factor, and the summation is over all possible states $R'$ of the many-particle system.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] where the summation is over all combinations of values of $n_{1},n_{2},\ldots$ which obey the Pauli exclusion principle, and $n_{r}=0$ = 0 or 1 for each r .
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] where the upper index $(i)$ on the summation sign indicates that the sum is not over $n_{i}$ and is subject to the constraint that the total number of particles associated with the summation is $N_{i}=N-n_{i}$ .
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Like the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution and the Bose–Einstein distribution, the Fermi–Dirac distribution can also be derived by the Darwin–Fowler method of mean values.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] A result can be achieved by directly analyzing the multiplicities of the system and using Lagrange multipliers.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Suppose we have a number of energy levels, labeled by index *i*, each level having energy ε*i* and containing a total of *ni* particles.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Suppose each level contains *gi* distinct sublevels, all of which have the same energy, and which are distinguishable.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] For example, two particles may have different momenta (i.e. their momenta may be along different directions), in which case they are distinguishable from each other, yet they can still have the same energy.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] The value of *gi* associated with level *i* is called the "degeneracy" of that energy level.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] The Pauli exclusion principle states that only one fermion can occupy any such sublevel.
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] For example, distributing two particles in three sublevels will give population numbers of 110, 101, or 011 for a total of three ways which equals 3!/(2!1!).
[src:statistical-physics/fermi-dirac-statistics] Following the same procedure used in deriving the Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics, we wish to find the set of *ni* for which *W* is maximized, subject to the constraint that there be a fixed number of particles and a fixed energy.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In statistical mechanics, the **grand canonical ensemble** (also known as the **macrocanonical ensemble**) is the statistical ensemble that is used to represent the possible states of a mechanical system of particles that are in thermodynamic equilibrium (thermal and chemical) with a reservoir.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The system is said to be open in the sense that the system can exchange energy and particles with a reservoir, so that various possible states of the system can differ in both their total energy and total number of particles.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The system's volume, shape, and other external coordinates are kept the same in all possible states of the system.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The thermodynamic variables of the grand canonical ensemble are chemical potential (symbol: *µ*) and absolute temperature (symbol: *T*).
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The ensemble is also dependent on mechanical variables such as volume (symbol: *V*), which influence the nature of the system's internal states.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] This ensemble is therefore sometimes called the ***µVT* ensemble**, as each of these three quantities are constants of the ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In simple terms, the grand canonical ensemble assigns a probability *P* to each distinct microstate given by the following exponential: $P=e^{{(\Omega +\mu N-E)}/{(kT)}},$ where *N* is the number of particles in the microstate and *E* is the total energy of the microstate.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The number Ω is known as the grand potential and is constant for the ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] However, the probabilities and Ω will vary if different *µ*, *V*, *T* are selected.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The grand potential Ω serves two roles: to provide a normalization factor for the probability distribution (the probabilities, over the complete set of microstates, must add up to one); and, many important ensemble averages can be directly calculated from the function Ω(*µ*, *V*, *T*).
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] However, these particle numbers should be defined carefully (see the note on particle number conservation below).
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The distribution of the grand canonical ensemble is called generalized Boltzmann distribution by some authors.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The grand canonical ensemble provides a natural setting for an exact derivation of the Fermi–Dirac statistics or Bose–Einstein statistics for a system of non-interacting quantum particles (see examples below).
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The equations in this article (in terms of grand potential) may be restated in terms of the grand partition function by simple mathematical manipulations.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The grand canonical ensemble is the ensemble that describes the possible states of an isolated system that is in thermal and chemical equilibrium with a reservoir (the derivation proceeds along lines analogous to the heat bath derivation of the normal canonical ensemble, and can be found in Reif).
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The grand canonical ensemble applies to systems of any size, small or large; it is only necessary to assume that the reservoir with which it is in contact is much larger (i.e., to take the macroscopic limit).
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The condition that the system is isolated is necessary in order to ensure it has well-defined thermodynamic quantities and evolution.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In practice, however, it is desirable to apply the grand canonical ensemble to describe systems that are in direct contact with the reservoir, since it is that contact that ensures the equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The use of the grand canonical ensemble in these cases is usually justified either 1) by assuming that the contact is weak, or 2) by incorporating a part of the reservoir connection into the system under analysis, so that the connection's influence on the region of interest is correctly modeled.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Alternatively, theoretical approaches can be used to model the influence of the connection, yielding an open statistical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Another case in which the grand canonical ensemble appears is when considering a system that is large and thermodynamic (a system that is "in equilibrium with itself").
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Even if the exact conditions of the system do not actually allow for variations in energy or particle number, the grand canonical ensemble can be used to simplify calculations of some thermodynamic properties.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The reason for this is that various thermodynamic ensembles (microcanonical, canonical) become equivalent in some aspects to the grand canonical ensemble, once the system is very large.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Of course, for small systems, the different ensembles are no longer equivalent even in the mean.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] As a result, the grand canonical ensemble can be highly inaccurate when applied to small systems of fixed particle number, such as atomic nuclei.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The usefulness of the grand canonical ensemble is illustrated in the examples below.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In each case the grand potential is calculated on the basis of the relationship $\Omega =-kT\ln \left(\sum _{\text{microstates}}e^{{(\mu N-E)}/{(kT)}}\right)$ which is required for the microstates' probabilities to add up to 1.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In the special case of a quantum system of many *non-interacting* particles, the thermodynamics are simple to compute.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Since the particles are non-interacting, one can compute a series of single-particle stationary states, each of which represent a separable part that can be included into the total quantum state of the system.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] For now let us refer to these single-particle stationary states as *orbitals* (to avoid confusing these "states" with the total many-body state), with the provision that each possible internal particle property (spin or polarization) counts as a separate orbital.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Each orbital may be occupied by a particle (or particles), or may be empty.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Since the particles are non-interacting, we may take the viewpoint that *each orbital forms a separate thermodynamic system*.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Thus each orbital is a grand canonical ensemble unto itself, one so simple that its statistics can be immediately derived here.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Focusing on just one orbital labelled *i*, the total energy for a microstate of *N**i* particles in this orbital will be *N**i**ϵ**i*, where *ϵ**i* is the characteristic energy level of that orbital.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In each case the value $\textstyle \langle N_{i}\rangle =-{\tfrac {\partial \Omega _{i}}{\partial \mu }}$ gives the thermodynamic average number of particles on the orbital: the Fermi–Dirac distribution for fermions, and the Bose–Einstein distribution for bosons.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Considering again the entire system, the total grand potential is found by adding up the Ω*i* for all orbitals.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In classical mechanics it is also possible to consider indistinguishable particles (in fact, indistinguishability is a prerequisite for defining a chemical potential in a consistent manner; all particles of a given kind must be interchangeable).
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] We can consider a region of the single-particle phase space with approximately uniform energy *ϵ**i* to be an "orbital" labelled *i*.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Two complications arise since this orbital actually encompasses many (infinite) distinct states.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The grand canonical ensemble can be used to predict whether an atom prefers to be in a neutral state or ionized state.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] An atom is able to exist in ionized states with more or fewer electrons compared to neutral.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] As shown below, ionized states may be thermodynamically preferred depending on the environment.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Here Δ*E*I and Δ*E*A are the atom's ionization energy and electron affinity, respectively; *ϕ* is the local electrostatic potential in the vacuum nearby the atom, and −*q* is the electron charge.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] This value is determined by the environment around the atom.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In order for a particle number to have an associated chemical potential, it must be conserved during the internal dynamics of the system, and only able to change when the system exchanges particles with an external reservoir.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] If the particles can be created out of energy during the dynamics of the system, then an associated *µN* term must not appear in the probability expression for the grand canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In effect, this is the same as requiring that *µ* = 0 for that kind of particle.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Such is the case for photons in a black cavity, whose number regularly change due to absorption and emission on the cavity walls.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The precise mathematical expression for statistical ensembles has a distinct form depending on the type of mechanics under consideration (quantum or classical), as the notion of a "microstate" is considerably different.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In quantum mechanics, the grand canonical ensemble affords a simple description since diagonalization provides a set of distinct microstates of a system, each with well-defined energy and particle number.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The classical mechanical case is more complex as it involves not stationary states but instead an integral over canonical phase space.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Note that for the grand ensemble, the basis states of the operators *Ĥ*, *N̂*1, etc. are all states with *multiple particles* in Fock space, and the density matrix is defined on the same basis.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Since the energy and particle numbers are all separately conserved, these operators are mutually commuting.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In a system of particles, the number of degrees of freedom *n* depends on the number of particles in a way that depends on the physical situation.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] For example, in a three-dimensional gas of monoatoms *n* = 3*N*, however in molecular gases there will also be rotational and vibrational degrees of freedom.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] A well-known problem in the statistical mechanics of fluids (gases, liquids, plasmas) is how to treat particles that are similar or identical in nature: should they be regarded as distinguishable or not?
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] If the permutations of similar particles are regarded to count as distinct states, then the factor *C* above is simply *C* = 1.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] From this point of view, ensembles include every permuted state as a separate microstate.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] Although appearing benign at first, this leads to a problem of severely non-extensive entropy in the canonical ensemble, known today as the Gibbs paradox.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In the grand canonical ensemble a further logical inconsistency occurs: the number of distinguishable permutations depends not only on how many particles are in the system, but also on how many particles are in the reservoir (since the system may exchange particles with a reservoir).
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In this case the entropy and chemical potential are non-extensive but also badly defined, depending on a parameter (reservoir size) that should be irrelevant.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] To solve these issues it is necessary that the exchange of two similar particles (within the system, or between the system and reservoir) must not be regarded as giving a distinct state of the system.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] In order to incorporate this fact, integrals are still carried over full phase space but the result is divided by $C=N_{1}!N_{2}!\cdots N_{s}!,$ which is the number of different permutations possible.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] The division by *C* neatly corrects the overcounting that occurs in the integral over all phase space.
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] It is of course possible to include distinguishable *types* of particles in the grand canonical ensemble—each distinguishable type i is tracked by a separate particle counter $N_{i}$ and chemical potential $\mu _{i}$ .
[src:statistical-physics/grand-canonical-ensemble] As a result, the only consistent way to include "fully distinguishable" particles in the grand canonical ensemble is to consider every possible distinguishable type of those particles, and to track each and every possible type with a separate particle counter and separate chemical potential.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In statistical mechanics, the **microcanonical ensemble** is a statistical ensemble that represents the possible states of a mechanical system whose total energy is exactly specified.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The system is assumed to be isolated in the sense that it cannot exchange energy or particles with its environment, so that (by conservation of energy) the energy of the system does not change with time.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The primary macroscopic variables of the microcanonical ensemble are the total number of particles in the system (symbol: *N*), the system's volume (symbol: *V*), as well as the total energy in the system (symbol: *E*).
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Each of these is assumed to be constant in the ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] For this reason, the microcanonical ensemble is sometimes called the ***NVE* ensemble**.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In simple terms, the microcanonical ensemble is defined by assigning an equal probability to every microstate whose energy falls within a range centered at *E*.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] All other microstates are given a probability of zero.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Since the probabilities must add up to 1, the probability *P* is the reciprocal of the number of microstates *W* within the range of energy, $P=1/W,$ The range of energy is then reduced in width until it is infinitesimally narrow, still centered at *E*.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In the limit of this process, the microcanonical ensemble is obtained.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Because of its connection with the elementary assumptions of equilibrium statistical mechanics (particularly the postulate of a priori equal probabilities), the microcanonical ensemble is an important conceptual building block in the theory.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] It is sometimes considered to be the fundamental distribution of equilibrium statistical mechanics.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] It is also useful in some numerical applications, such as molecular dynamics.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] On the other hand, most nontrivial systems are mathematically cumbersome to describe in the microcanonical ensemble, and there are also ambiguities regarding the definitions of entropy and temperature.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] For these reasons, other ensembles are often preferred for theoretical calculations.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The applicability of the microcanonical ensemble to real-world systems depends on the importance of energy fluctuations, which may result from interactions between the system and its environment as well as uncontrolled factors in preparing the system.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Generally, fluctuations are negligible if a system is macroscopically large, or if it is manufactured with precisely known energy and thereafter maintained in near isolation from its environment.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In such cases the microcanonical ensemble is applicable.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Otherwise, different ensembles are more appropriate – such as the canonical ensemble (fluctuating energy) or the grand canonical ensemble (fluctuating energy and particle number).
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The fundamental thermodynamic potential of the microcanonical ensemble is entropy.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] There are at least three possible definitions, each given in terms of the phase volume function *v*(*E*).
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In classical mechanics *v*(*E*) this is the volume of the region of phase space where the energy is less than *E*.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In quantum mechanics *v*(*E*) is roughly the number of energy eigenstates with energy less than *E*; however this must be smoothed so that we can take its derivative (see the Precise expressions section for details on how this is done).
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In the microcanonical ensemble, the temperature is a derived quantity rather than an external control parameter.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] It is defined as the derivative of the chosen entropy with respect to energy.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] More generally, the correspondence between these ensemble-based definitions and their thermodynamic counterparts is not perfect, particularly for finite systems.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Under their strict definition, phase transitions correspond to nonanalytic behavior in the thermodynamic potential or its derivatives.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Using this definition, phase transitions in the microcanonical ensemble can occur in systems of any size.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] This contrasts with the canonical and grand canonical ensembles, for which phase transitions can occur only in the thermodynamic limit – i.e., in systems with infinitely many degrees of freedom.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Roughly speaking, the reservoirs defining the canonical or grand canonical ensembles introduce fluctuations that "smooth out" any nonanalytic behavior in the free energy of finite systems.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] This smoothing effect is usually negligible in macroscopic systems, which are sufficiently large that the free energy can approximate nonanalytic behavior exceedingly well.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] However, the technical difference in ensembles may be important in the theoretical analysis of small systems.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] For a given mechanical system (fixed *N*, *V*) and a given range of energy, the uniform distribution of probability *P* over microstates (as in the microcanonical ensemble) maximizes the ensemble average −⟨log *P*⟩.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Early work in statistical mechanics by Ludwig Boltzmann led to his eponymous entropy equation for a system of a given total energy, *S* = *k*B log *W*, where *W* is the number of distinct states accessible by the system at that energy.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Boltzmann did not elaborate too deeply on what exactly constitutes the set of distinct states of a system, besides the special case of an ideal gas.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] This topic was investigated to completion by Josiah Willard Gibbs who developed the generalized statistical mechanics for arbitrary mechanical systems, and defined the microcanonical ensemble described in this article.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Gibbs investigated carefully the analogies between the microcanonical ensemble and thermodynamics, especially how they break down in the case of systems of few degrees of freedom.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] He introduced two further definitions of microcanonical entropy that do not depend on *ω* – the volume and surface entropy described above.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The volume entropy $S_{v}$ and associated temperature $T_{v}$ are closely analogous to thermodynamic entropy and temperature.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] It is possible to show exactly that $dE=T_{v}\,dS_{v}-\left\langle P\right\rangle dV,$ (⟨*P*⟩ is the ensemble average pressure) as expected for the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] A similar equation can be found for the surface entropy $S_{s}$ (or Boltzmann entropy $S_{\text{B}}$ ) and its associated temperature *T*s, however the "pressure" in this equation is a complicated quantity unrelated to the average pressure.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The microcanonical temperatures $T_{v}$ and $T_{s}$ are not entirely satisfactory in their analogy to temperature as defined using a canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Outside of the thermodynamic limit, a number of artefacts occur.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The preferred solution to these problems is avoid use of the microcanonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In many realistic cases a system is thermostatted to a heat bath so that the energy is not precisely known.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Then, a more accurate description is the canonical ensemble or grand canonical ensemble, both of which have complete correspondence to thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The precise mathematical expression for a statistical ensemble depends on the kind of mechanics under consideration – quantum or classical – since the notion of a "microstate" is considerably different in these two cases.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In quantum mechanics, diagonalization provides a discrete set of microstates with specific energies.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The classical mechanical case involves instead an integral over canonical phase space, and the size of microstates in phase space can be chosen somewhat arbitrarily.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] To construct the microcanonical ensemble, it is necessary in both types of mechanics to first specify a range of energy.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In the expressions below the function $f{\left({\tfrac {H-E}{\omega }}\right)}$ (a function of *H*, peaking at *E* with width *ω*) will be used to represent the range of energy in which to include states.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Example of microcanonical ensemble for a quantum system consisting of one particle in a potential well.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] An ensemble containing only those states within a narrow interval of energy.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] As the energy width is taken to zero, a microcanonical ensemble is obtained (provided the interval contains at least one state).
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The microcanonical ensemble can be written using bra–ket notation, in terms of the system's energy eigenstates and energy eigenvalues.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The microcanonical ensemble is defined by taking the limit of the density matrix as the energy width goes to zero, however a problematic situation occurs once the energy width becomes smaller than the spacing between energy levels.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] For very small energy width, the ensemble does not exist at all for most values of *E*, since no states fall within the range.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] When the ensemble does exist, it typically only contains one (or two) states, since in a complex system the energy levels are only ever equal by accident (see random matrix theory for more discussion on this point).
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Moreover, the state-volume function also increases only in discrete increments, and so its derivative is only ever infinite or zero, making it difficult to define the density of states.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Example of microcanonical ensemble for a classical system consisting of one particle in a potential well.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] An ensemble restricted to only those states within a narrow interval of energy.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] This ensemble appears as a thin shell in phase space.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] As the energy width is taken to zero, a microcanonical ensemble is obtained.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In classical mechanics, an ensemble is represented by a joint probability density function *ρ*(*p*1, ...
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] *q**n*) defined over the system's phase space.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The phase space has *n* generalized coordinates called *q*1, ...
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] *q**n*, and *n* associated canonical momenta called *p*1, ...
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Again, the value of *W* is determined by demanding that *ρ* is a normalized probability density function: $W=\int \cdots \int {\frac {1}{h^{n}C}}f{\left({\tfrac {H-E}{\omega }}\right)}\,dp_{1}\cdots dq_{n}$ This integral is taken over the entire phase space.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] As the energy width *ω* is taken to zero, the value of *W* decreases in proportion to *ω* as *W* = *ω* (*dv*/*dE*).
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Based on the above definition, the microcanonical ensemble can be visualized as an infinitesimally thin shell in phase space, centered on a constant-energy surface.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] Although the microcanonical ensemble is confined to this surface, it is not necessarily uniformly distributed over that surface: if the gradient of energy in phase space varies, then the microcanonical ensemble is "thicker" (more concentrated) in some parts of the surface than others.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] This feature is an unavoidable consequence of requiring that the microcanonical ensemble is a steady-state ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The fundamental quantity in the microcanonical ensemble is $W(E,V,N)$ , which is equal to the phase space volume compatible with given $(E,V,N)$ .
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] From W , all thermodynamic quantities can be calculated.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] For an ideal gas, the energy is independent of the particle positions, which therefore contribute a factor of $V^{N}$ to W .
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The momenta, by contrast, are constrained to a $3N$ -dimensional (hyper-)spherical shell of radius ${\sqrt {2mE}}$ ; their contribution is equal to the surface volume of this shell.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The resulting expression for W is: $W={\frac {V^{N}}{N!}}{\frac {2\pi ^{3N/2}}{\Gamma (3N/2)}}\left(2mE\right)^{(3N-1)/2}$ where $\Gamma (\cdot )$ is the gamma function, and the factor $N!$ has been included to account for the indistinguishability of particles (see Gibbs paradox).
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The temperature is given by ${\frac {1}{T}}\equiv {\frac {\partial S}{\partial E}}={\frac {3}{2}}{\frac {Nk_{\text{B}}}{E}}$ which agrees with analogous result from the kinetic theory of gases.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The microcanonical phase volume can also be calculated explicitly for an ideal gas in a uniform gravitational field.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The results are stated below for a 3-dimensional ideal gas of N particles, each with mass m , confined in a thermally isolated container that is infinitely long in the *z*-direction and has constant cross-sectional area A .
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The gravitational field is assumed to act in the minus *z* direction with strength g .
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] The gas density $\rho (z)$ as a function of height z can be obtained by integrating over the phase volume coordinates.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In the limit $N\to \infty$ , the microcanonical and canonical expressions coincide; however, they differ for finite N .
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] In particular, in the microcanonical ensemble, the positions and velocities are not statistically independent.
[src:statistical-physics/microcanonical-ensemble] As a result, the kinetic temperature, defined as the average kinetic energy in a given volume $A\,dz$ , is nonuniform throughout the container: $T_{\text{kinetic}}={\frac {3E}{5N-2}}\left(1-{\frac {mgz}{E}}\right)$ By contrast, the temperature is uniform in the canonical ensemble, for any N .
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In physics, a **partition function** describes the statistical properties of a system in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Partition functions are functions of the thermodynamic state variables, such as the temperature and volume.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Most of the aggregate thermodynamic variables of the system, such as the total energy, free energy, entropy, and pressure, can be expressed in terms of the partition function or its derivatives.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The partition function is dimensionless.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Each partition function is constructed to represent a particular statistical ensemble (which, in turn, corresponds to a particular free energy).
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The most common statistical ensembles have named partition functions.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The **canonical partition function** applies to a canonical ensemble, in which the system is allowed to exchange heat with the environment at fixed temperature, volume, and number of particles.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The **grand canonical partition function** applies to a grand canonical ensemble, in which the system can exchange both heat and particles with the environment, at fixed temperature, volume, and chemical potential.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Other types of partition functions can be defined for different circumstances; see partition function (mathematics) for generalizations.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The partition function has many physical meanings, as discussed in Meaning and significance.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Initially, let us assume that a thermodynamically large system is in thermal contact with the environment, with a temperature *T*, and both the volume of the system and the number of constituent particles are fixed.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] A collection of this kind of system comprises an ensemble called a canonical ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The appropriate mathematical expression for the canonical partition function depends on the degrees of freedom of the system, whether the context is classical mechanics or quantum mechanics, and whether the spectrum of states is discrete or continuous.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The exponential factor $e^{-\beta E_{i}}$ is otherwise known as the Boltzmann factor.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] There are multiple approaches to deriving the partition function.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The following derivation follows the more powerful and general information-theoretic Jaynesian maximum entropy approach.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] According to the second law of thermodynamics, a system assumes a configuration of maximum entropy at thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Thus the canonical partition function Z becomes $Z\equiv \sum _{i}e^{-\beta E_{i}},$ where $\beta \equiv 1/(k_{\text{B}}T)$ is defined as the thermodynamic beta.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In classical mechanics, the position and momentum variables of a particle can vary continuously, so the set of microstates is actually uncountable.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In *classical* statistical mechanics, it is rather inaccurate to express the partition function as a sum of discrete terms.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In this case we must describe the partition function using an integral rather than a sum.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] To make it into a dimensionless quantity, we must divide it by *h*, which is some quantity with units of action (usually taken to be the Planck constant).
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The reason for the factorial factor *N*! is discussed below.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The extra constant factor introduced in the denominator was introduced because, unlike the discrete form, the continuous form shown above is not dimensionless.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] As stated in the previous section, to make it into a dimensionless quantity, we must divide it by *h*3*N* (where *h* is usually taken to be the Planck constant).
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The dimension of $e^{-\beta {\hat {H}}}$ is the number of energy eigenstates of the system.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In systems with multiple quantum states *s* sharing the same energy *Es*, it is said that the energy levels of the system are degenerate.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The above treatment applies to *quantum* statistical mechanics, where a physical system inside a finite-sized box will typically have a discrete set of energy eigenstates, which we can use as the states *s* above.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In quantum mechanics, the partition function can be more formally written as a trace over the state space (which is independent of the choice of basis): $Z=\operatorname {tr} (e^{-\beta {\hat {H}}}),$ where *Ĥ* is the quantum Hamiltonian operator.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The exponential of an operator can be defined using the exponential power series.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The classical form of *Z* is recovered when the trace is expressed in terms of coherent states and when quantum-mechanical uncertainties in the position and momentum of a particle are regarded as negligible.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Formally, using bra–ket notation, one inserts under the trace for each degree of freedom the identity: ${\boldsymbol {1}}=\int |x,p\rangle \langle x,p|{\frac {dx\,dp}{h}},$ where |*x*, *p*⟩ is a normalised Gaussian wavepacket centered at position *x* and momentum *p*.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] If Δ*x* and Δ*p* can be regarded as zero, the action of *Ĥ* reduces to multiplication by the classical Hamiltonian, and *Z* reduces to the classical configuration integral.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] For simplicity, we will use the discrete form of the partition function in this section.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Our results will apply equally well to the continuous form.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Consider a system *S* embedded into a heat bath *B*.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Let the total energy of both systems be *E*.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Let *pi* denote the probability that the system *S* is in a particular microstate, *i*, with energy *Ei*.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Equivalently, *pi* will be proportional to the number of microstates of the heat bath *B* with energy *E* − *Ei*.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] We then normalize this by dividing by the total number of microstates in which the constraints we have imposed on the entire system; both S and the heat bath; hold.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In order to demonstrate the usefulness of the partition function, let us calculate the thermodynamic value of the total energy.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] This provides us with a method for calculating the expected values of many microscopic quantities.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] We add the quantity artificially to the microstate energies (or, in the language of quantum mechanics, to the Hamiltonian), calculate the new partition function and expected value, and then set *λ* to zero in the final expression.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] This is analogous to the source field method used in the path integral formulation of quantum field theory.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In this section, we will state the relationships between the partition function and the various thermodynamic parameters of the system.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] These results can be derived using the method of the previous section and the various thermodynamic relations.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] In general, consider the extensive variable *X* and intensive variable *Y* where *X* and *Y* form a pair of conjugate variables.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The sign will depend on the specific definitions of the variables *X* and *Y*.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] An example would be *X* = volume and *Y* = pressure.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Suppose a system is subdivided into *N* sub-systems with negligible interaction energy, that is, we can assume the particles are essentially non-interacting.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] However, there is a well-known exception to this rule.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] If the sub-systems are actually identical particles, in the quantum mechanical sense that they are impossible to distinguish even in principle, the total partition function must be divided by a *N*!
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] This is to ensure that we do not "over-count" the number of microstates.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] While this may seem like a strange requirement, it is actually necessary to preserve the existence of a thermodynamic limit for such systems.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] It may not be obvious why the partition function, as we have defined it above, is an important quantity.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The partition function is a function of the temperature *T* and the microstate energies *E*1, *E*2, *E*3, etc.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The microstate energies are determined by other thermodynamic variables, such as the number of particles and the volume, as well as microscopic quantities like the mass of the constituent particles.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] This dependence on microscopic variables is the central point of statistical mechanics.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] With a model of the microscopic constituents of a system, one can calculate the microstate energies, and thus the partition function, which will then allow us to calculate all the other thermodynamic properties of the system.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The partition function can be related to thermodynamic properties because it has a very important statistical meaning.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] This is the reason for calling *Z* the "partition function": it encodes how the probabilities are partitioned among the different microstates, based on their individual energies.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Other partition functions for different ensembles divide up the probabilities based on other macrostate variables.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] As an example: the partition function for the isothermal-isobaric ensemble, the generalized Boltzmann distribution, divides up probabilities based on particle number, pressure, and temperature.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The energy is replaced by the characteristic potential of that ensemble, the Gibbs Free Energy.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The letter *Z* stands for the German word *Zustandssumme*, "sum over states".
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The usefulness of the partition function stems from the fact that the macroscopic thermodynamic quantities of a system can be related to its microscopic details through the derivatives of its partition function.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] Finding the partition function is also equivalent to performing a Laplace transform of the density of states function from the energy domain to the *β* domain, and the inverse Laplace transform of the partition function reclaims the state density function of energies.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] We can define a **grand canonical partition function** for a grand canonical ensemble, which describes the statistics of a constant-volume system that can exchange both heat and particles with a reservoir.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The reservoir has a constant temperature *T*, and a chemical potential *μ*.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The number of microstates in the grand canonical ensemble may be much larger than in the canonical ensemble, since here we consider not only variations in energy but also in particle number.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] An important application of the grand canonical ensemble is in deriving exactly the statistics of a non-interacting many-body quantum gas (Fermi–Dirac statistics for fermions, Bose–Einstein statistics for bosons), however it is much more generally applicable than that.
[src:statistical-physics/partition-function-statistical-mechanics] The grand canonical ensemble may also be used to describe classical systems, or even interacting quantum gases.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In physics, **statistical mechanics** is a mathematical framework that applies statistical methods and probability theory to large assemblies of microscopic entities.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Sometimes called **statistical physics** or **statistical thermodynamics**, its applications include many problems in a wide variety of fields such as biology, neuroscience, computer science, information theory and sociology.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Its main purpose is to clarify the properties of matter in aggregate, in terms of physical laws governing atomic motion.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] While classical thermodynamics is primarily concerned with thermodynamic equilibrium, statistical mechanics has been applied in non-equilibrium statistical mechanics to the issues of microscopically modeling the speed of irreversible processes that are driven by imbalances.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Examples of such processes include chemical reactions and flows of particles and heat.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The fluctuation–dissipation theorem is the basic knowledge obtained from applying non-equilibrium statistical mechanics to study the simplest non-equilibrium situation of a steady state current flow in a system of many particles.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In 1738, Swiss physicist and mathematician Daniel Bernoulli published *Hydrodynamica* which laid the basis for the kinetic theory of gases.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In this work, Bernoulli posited the argument, still used to this day, that gases consist of great numbers of molecules moving in all directions, that their impact on a surface causes the gas pressure that we feel, and that what we experience as heat is simply the kinetic energy of their motion.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In 1859, after reading a paper on the diffusion of molecules by Rudolf Clausius, the Scottish physicist Maxwell formulated the Maxwell distribution of molecular velocities, which gave the proportion of molecules having a certain velocity in a specific range.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] This was the first-ever statistical law in physics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Maxwell also gave the first mechanical argument that molecular collisions entail an equalization of temperatures and hence a tendency towards equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Five years later, in 1864, Boltzmann, a young student in Vienna, came across Maxwell's paper and spent much of his life developing the subject further.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical mechanics was initiated in the 1870s with the work of Boltzmann, much of which was collectively published in his 1896 *Lectures on Gas Theory*.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Boltzmann's original papers on the statistical interpretation of thermodynamics, the *H*-theorem, transport theory, thermal equilibrium, the equation of state of gases, and similar subjects, occupy about 2,000 pages in the proceedings of the Vienna Academy and other societies.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Boltzmann introduced the concept of an equilibrium statistical ensemble and also investigated for the first time non-equilibrium statistical mechanics, with his *H*-theorem.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The term "statistical mechanics" was coined by the American mathematical physicist Gibbs in 1884.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] "Probabilistic mechanics" might today seem a more appropriate term, but "statistical mechanics" is firmly entrenched.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Shortly before his death, Gibbs published in 1902 *Elementary Principles in Statistical Mechanics*, a book which formalized statistical mechanics as a fully general approach to address all mechanical systems—macroscopic or microscopic, gaseous or non-gaseous.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Gibbs' methods were initially derived in the framework of classical mechanics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] However, they were of such generality that they were found to adapt easily to the later quantum mechanics, and still form the foundation of statistical mechanics to this day.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In physics, two types of mechanics are usually examined: classical mechanics and quantum mechanics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Using these two concepts, the state at any other time, past or future, can in principle be calculated.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical mechanics fills this disconnection between the laws of mechanics and the practical experience of incomplete knowledge, by adding some uncertainty about which state the system is in.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Whereas ordinary mechanics only considers the behaviour of a single state, statistical mechanics introduces the statistical ensemble, which is a large collection of virtual, independent copies of the system in various states.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The statistical ensemble is a probability distribution over all possible states of the system.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In classical statistical mechanics, the ensemble is a probability distribution over phase points (as opposed to a single phase point in ordinary mechanics), usually represented as a distribution in a phase space with canonical coordinate axes.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In quantum statistical mechanics, the ensemble is a probability distribution over pure states and can be compactly summarized as a density matrix.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] These two meanings are equivalent for many purposes, and will be used interchangeably in this article.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] However the probability is interpreted, each state in the ensemble evolves over time according to the equation of motion.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Thus, the ensemble itself (the probability distribution over states) also evolves, as the virtual systems in the ensemble move through different states.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The ensemble evolution is given by the Liouville equation (classical mechanics) or the von Neumann equation (quantum mechanics).
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] These equations can be derived by applying the mechanical equation of motion separately to each virtual system contained in the ensemble, with the probability of each virtual system conserved over time as it evolves.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] One special class of ensemble is those ensembles that do not evolve over time.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] These ensembles are known as *equilibrium ensembles* and their condition is known as *statistical equilibrium*.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical equilibrium occurs if, for each state in the ensemble, the ensemble also contains all of its future and past states with probabilities equal to the probability of being in that state.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] (By contrast, *mechanical equilibrium* is a state with a balance of forces that has ceased to evolve.) The study of equilibrium ensembles of isolated systems is the focus of statistical thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Non-equilibrium statistical mechanics addresses the more general case of ensembles that change over time, and/or ensembles of non-isolated systems.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The primary goal of statistical thermodynamics (also known as equilibrium statistical mechanics) is to derive the classical thermodynamics of materials in terms of the properties of their constituent particles and the interactions between them.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In other words, statistical thermodynamics provides a connection between the macroscopic properties of materials in thermodynamic equilibrium, and the microscopic behaviours and motions occurring inside the material.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Whereas statistical mechanics proper involves dynamics, here the attention is focused on *statistical equilibrium* (steady state).
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical equilibrium does not mean that the particles have stopped moving (mechanical equilibrium), rather, only that the ensemble is not evolving.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] A sufficient (but not necessary) condition for statistical equilibrium with an isolated system is that the probability distribution is a function only of conserved properties (total energy, total particle numbers, etc.).
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] There are many different equilibrium ensembles that can be considered, and only some of them correspond to thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Additional postulates are necessary to motivate why the ensemble for a given system should have one form or another.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] A common approach found in many textbooks is to take the *equal a priori probability postulate*.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The equal a priori probability postulate therefore provides a motivation for the microcanonical ensemble described below.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Other fundamental postulates for statistical mechanics have also been proposed.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] For example, recent studies show that the theory of statistical mechanics can be built without the equal a priori probability postulate.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Thermodynamic state functions are described by ensemble averages of random variables.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The entropy as defined by Gibbs entropy formula matches with the entropy as defined in classical thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] There are three equilibrium ensembles with a simple form that can be defined for any isolated system bounded inside a finite volume.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] These are the most often discussed ensembles in statistical thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In the macroscopic limit (defined below) they all correspond to classical thermodynamics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] describes a system with a precisely given energy and fixed composition (precise number of particles).
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The microcanonical ensemble contains with equal probability each possible state that is consistent with that energy and composition.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The canonical ensemble contains states of varying energy but identical composition; the different states in the ensemble are accorded different probabilities depending on their total energy.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] describes a system with non-fixed composition (uncertain particle numbers) that is in thermal and chemical equilibrium with a thermodynamic reservoir.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The grand canonical ensemble contains states of varying energy and varying numbers of particles; the different states in the ensemble are accorded different probabilities depending on their total energy and total particle numbers.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] For systems containing many particles (the thermodynamic limit), all three of the ensembles listed above tend to give identical behaviour.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] It is then simply a matter of mathematical convenience which ensemble is used.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The Gibbs theorem about equivalence of ensembles was developed into the theory of concentration of measure phenomenon, which has applications in many areas of science, from functional analysis to methods of artificial intelligence and big data technology.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In these cases the correct thermodynamic ensemble must be chosen as there are observable differences between these ensembles not just in the size of fluctuations, but also in average quantities such as the distribution of particles.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The correct ensemble is that which corresponds to the way the system has been prepared and characterized—in other words, the ensemble that reflects the knowledge about that system.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Once the partition function for an ensemble has been determined for a given system, that system is considered "solved," as all macroscopic thermodynamic observables can be derived from it via partial derivatives.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Calculating the partition function of a thermodynamic ensemble is often a formidable challenge, however, as it requires performing a summation or integration over every possible microstate available to the system.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] While certain idealized models allow for exact analytical solutions, most realistic many-body systems are too complex for such a treatment.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Consequently, various approximation techniques—such as mean-field theory, perturbation expansions, or Monte Carlo simulations—are employed to estimate the partition function and compute the average values of physical quantities.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] There are some cases which allow exact solutions.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Although some problems in statistical physics can be solved analytically using approximations and expansions, most current research utilizes the large processing power of modern computers to simulate or approximate solutions.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] A common approach to statistical problems is to use a Monte Carlo simulation to yield insight into the properties of a complex system.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Monte Carlo methods are important in computational physics, physical chemistry, and related fields, and have diverse applications including medical physics, where they are used to model radiation transport for radiation dosimetry calculations.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The Monte Carlo method examines just a few of the possible states of the system, with the states chosen randomly (with a fair weight).
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] As long as these states form a representative sample of the whole set of states of the system, the approximate characteristic function is obtained.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] As more and more random samples are included, the errors are reduced to an arbitrarily low level.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] All of these processes occur over time with characteristic rates.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] These rates are important in engineering.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The field of non-equilibrium statistical mechanics is concerned with understanding these non-equilibrium processes at the microscopic level.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In principle, non-equilibrium statistical mechanics could be mathematically exact: ensembles for an isolated system evolve over time according to deterministic equations such as Liouville's equation or its quantum equivalent, the von Neumann equation.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] These equations are the result of applying the mechanical equations of motion independently to each state in the ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] These ensemble evolution equations inherit much of the complexity of the underlying mechanical motion, and so exact solutions are very difficult to obtain.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Moreover, the ensemble evolution equations are fully reversible and do not destroy information (the ensemble's Gibbs entropy is preserved).
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In order to make headway in modelling irreversible processes, it is necessary to consider additional factors besides probability and reversible mechanics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Non-equilibrium mechanics is therefore an active area of theoretical research as the range of validity of these additional assumptions continues to be explored.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] A few approaches are described in the following subsections.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] One approach to non-equilibrium statistical mechanics is to incorporate stochastic (random) behaviour into the system.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Stochastic behaviour destroys information contained in the ensemble.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] These correlations appear as chaotic or pseudorandom influences on the variables of interest.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] By replacing these correlations with randomness proper, the calculations can be made much easier.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Another important class of non-equilibrium statistical mechanical models deals with systems that are only very slightly perturbed from equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] With very small perturbations, the response can be analysed in linear response theory.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] A remarkable result, as formalized by the fluctuation–dissipation theorem, is that the response of a system when near equilibrium is precisely related to the fluctuations that occur when the system is in total equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Essentially, a system that is slightly away from equilibrium—whether put there by external forces or by fluctuations—relaxes towards equilibrium in the same way, since the system cannot tell the difference or "know" how it came to be away from equilibrium.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] This provides an indirect avenue for obtaining numbers such as ohmic conductivity and thermal conductivity by extracting results from equilibrium statistical mechanics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Since equilibrium statistical mechanics is mathematically well defined and (in some cases) more amenable for calculations, the fluctuation–dissipation connection can be a convenient shortcut for calculations in near-equilibrium statistical mechanics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] An advanced approach uses a combination of stochastic methods and linear response theory.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] The ensemble formalism can be used to analyze general mechanical systems with uncertainty in knowledge about the state of a system.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical physics explains and quantitatively describes superconductivity, superfluidity, turbulence, collective phenomena in solids and plasma, and the structural features of liquid.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] It underlies modern astrophysics and the virial theorem.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In solid state physics, statistical physics aids the study of liquid crystals, phase transitions, and critical phenomena.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Many experimental studies of matter are entirely based on the statistical description of a system.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] These include the scattering of cold neutrons, X-ray, visible light, and more.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical physics also plays a role in materials science, nuclear physics, astrophysics, chemistry, biology and medicine (e.g. study of the spread of infectious diseases).
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Analytical and computational techniques derived from statistical physics of disordered systems, can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g. to analyze the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] Quantum statistical mechanics is statistical mechanics applied to quantum mechanical systems.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] In quantum mechanics, a statistical ensemble (probability distribution over possible quantum states) is described by a density operator *S*, which is a non-negative, self-adjoint, trace-class operator of trace 1 on the Hilbert space *H* describing the quantum system.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] This can be shown under various mathematical formalisms for quantum mechanics.
[src:statistical-physics/statistical-mechanics] One such formalism is provided by quantum logic.
